04931nam a22007335i 9780691194196DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911941967 a10.1515/97806911941962doi  a(DE-B1597)535187  a(OCoLC)1113926764  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0220002bisacsh04a933/.050922231 aGoodman, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJosephus's The Jewish War :bA Biography /cMartin Goodman. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b8 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLives of Great Religious Books ;v3300tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Beginnings -- tChapter 2. Early Years (100- 1450) -- tChapter 3. Rediscovery of the Greek Book (1450- 1750) -- tChapter 4. Controversy -- tEpilogue. The Present and Future of the Jewish War -- tAppendix. Passages with a Life of Their Own -- tNotes -- tFurther Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn essential introduction to Josephus's momentous war narrativeThe Jewish War is Josephus's superbly evocative account of the Jewish revolt against Rome, which was crushed in 70 CE with the siege of Jerusalem and the destruction of the Temple. Martin Goodman describes the life of this book, from its composition in Greek for a Roman readership to the myriad ways it touched the lives of Jews and Christians over the span of two millennia.The scion of a priestly Jewish family, Josephus became a rebel general at the start of the war. Captured by the enemy general Vespasian, Josephus predicted correctly that Vespasian would be the future emperor of Rome and thus witnessed the final stages of the siege of Jerusalem from the safety of the Roman camp and wrote his history of these cataclysmic events from a comfortable exile in Rome. His history enjoyed enormous popularity among Christians, who saw it as a testimony to the world that gave rise to their faith and a record of the suffering of the Jews due to their rejection of Christ. Jews were hardly aware of the book until the Renaissance. In the nineteenth century, Josephus's history became an important source for recovering Jewish history, yet Jewish enthusiasm for his stories of heroism-such as the doomed defense of Masada-has been tempered by suspicion of a writer who betrayed his own people.Goodman provides a concise biography of one of the greatest war narratives ever written, explaining why Josephus's book continues to hold such fascination today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aJewish historiansvBiography. 0aJewsxHistoryyRebellion, 66-73xHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig. Stud., Jewish Stud.2019 Englishz978311061074108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2019z9783110606508oZDB-23-DGF40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691194196zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691194196423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691194196.jpg  a978-3-11-061074-1  EBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig. Stud., Jewish Stud.2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS